{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530284"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:04:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:04:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14510"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14510"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.09,0.15,0.18,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7205"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111084"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7205"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93207"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"9485"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45124"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111084"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of a painless swelling in his left leg. The swelling has been gradually increasing in size. His medical history includes prostate cancer and bladder cancer, both treated with curative intent. Regular surveillance, most recently nine months ago, has not shown any evidence of recurrence of either malignancy. He takes no regular medications. He is a retired builder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 9 x 7 cm ill-defined firm swelling on the medial aspect of his left mid-thigh that appears to arise from the deep tissues. The mass is non-pulsatile and non-tender. Distal to this there is significant swelling of the leg up to the level of the upper thigh (Image). There is no overlying skin change or lymphadenopathy. Blood tests two months ago showed a prostate-specific antigen of 0.8 \u03bcg/L (\u0026lt;4.0), which was stable from previous results.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deep vein thrombosis","Varicose veins","Metastatic prostate cancer","Subcutaneous lipoma","Sarcoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suspicious for soft tissue sarcoma: a large (\u0026gt;5 cm), deep, firm mass that has grown progressively over months. In this patient\u0027s case this has resulted in chronic lymphatic obstruction, resulting in distal limb swelling and obvious limb asymmetry. The patient\u0027s age and history of previous malignancies are additional risk factors for neoplasia in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a painless mass arising from deep soft tissues. The size (\u0026gt;5 cm), deep location, and progressive growth over months are classic features. Soft tissue sarcomas can occur as primary malignancies or following radiation therapy for other cancers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeep vein thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute onset pain and swelling of the entire limb, often with associated warmth and erythema. It would be unusual for DVT to present as a focal mass, and the chronicity of six months would be highly unusual without other complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricose veins\u003C/strong\u003E are dilated, tortuous superficial veins that are visible through the skin. They typically present with multiple visible vessels rather than a single firm mass, and are usually accompanied by symptoms such as aching or heaviness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetastatic prostate cancer\u003C/strong\u003E should be considered, particularly given the patient\u0027s history. However, the recent surveillance showing no evidence of recurrence and the low prostate-specific antigen level make this less likely. Additionally the location in the thigh would be unusual for prostate metastases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous lipoma\u003C/strong\u003E is typically soft, mobile, and well-circumscribed rather than firm and ill-defined. While lipomas can be large, they are usually slow-growing over years rather than months and are located in the superficial tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe appropriate next step would be urgent referral for imaging (MRI) and biopsy to confirm the diagnosis and guide management. Any soft tissue mass that is deep, larger than 5 cm, or growing should be considered suspicious for sarcoma until proven otherwise.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Any soft tissue mass greater than 5 cm in an adult should be considered suspicious for sarcoma until proven otherwise.","Deep, firm, painless masses that are rapidly growing are concerning features for soft tissue sarcoma.","Previous malignancy increases the risk of developing subsequent primary cancers including sarcomas."],"references":["Renn A. Adejolu M, Messiou C, et al. Overview of malignant soft-tissue sarcomas of the limbs. Clin Radiol 2021; 76:940e2. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34607656/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93207"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14510"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21126"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21126"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/nq6tKZSmo0XFL26Bl3GI8SNqJVpPQd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/nq6tKZSmo0XFL26Bl3GI8SNqJVpPQd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93207"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-08T19:16:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-08T19:17:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7205"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111084"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"a